r of the Arabic-Islamic geographic tradition has not yet been scrutinised in detail. This volume addresses this desideratum and combines case studies from both traditions of geographic thinking. The contributions comprise in-depth analyses of individual geographical works as for example those of al-Idrisi or Lambert of Saint-Omer, different forms of presenting geographical knowledge such as TO-diagrams or globes as well as performative aspects of studying and meditating geographical knowledge. Focussing on texts as well as on maps, the contributions open up a comparative perspective on how religious knowledge influenced the way the world and its geography were perceived and described int the medieval world.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGeographyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aReligion and geography. 0aReligionxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aGeography.  acartography.  areligion.1 aBaumgärtner, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouloux, Nathalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDucène, Jean-Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtienne Du Bois, Raoul Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerro, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranz, Kurt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMauntel, Christoph , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaunte